vectorData.altText: That's right! The superior pharyngeal constrictor (H) forms the floor of the tonsillar bed.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Once you have exposed the palatoglossus (A)

and palatopharyngeus (B) muscles, focus your efforts on removing any mucosa and remaining tonsillar tissue in between these muscles to expose the bed of the tonsil, which is formed by fibres of the superior (C) and middle (D) constrictor muscles of the pharynx.

There are three constrictor muscles of the pharynx, superior middle and inferior. The fibres of these muscles are arranged circularly, and the muscles are organized like three cups stacked one inside the other. You will study the pharynx in more detail in lab 6.
